{"questionId":"2719527","questionHtml":"<p>Use mathematical induction to prove that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munderover><mtext>Σ</mtext><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>n</mi></munderover><mfrac><mi>r</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac></math> for all integers <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>1</mn></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>)</mo></math> be the proposition that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munderover><mtext>Σ</mtext><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>n</mi></munderover><mfrac><mi>r</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;for all integers,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p>\n<p>considering <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math>:</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>LHS</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>RHS</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math> and so <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math> is true&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>assume <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is true <em>ie</em>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munderover><mtext>Σ</mtext><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>k</mi></munderover><mfrac><mi>r</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Do not award <em><strong>M1</strong></em> for statements such as “let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi></math>” or “<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi></math> is true”. Subsequent marks after this <em><strong>M1</strong></em> are independent of this mark and can be awarded.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>considering <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math>:</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munderover><mtext>Σ</mtext><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></munderover><mfrac><mi>r</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><munderover><mtext>Σ</mtext><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>k</mi></munderover><mfrac><mi>r</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>(</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math> is true whenever <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is true and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math> is true, so <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is true (for all integers, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>1</mn></math>)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> To obtain the final <em><strong>R1</strong></em>, any four of the previous marks must have been awarded.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[7 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"2719527","referenceCode":"23M.1.AHL.TZ2.7","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Use mathematical induction to prove that Σr=1nr(r+1)!=1-1(n+1)! for all integers n≥1.","paper":"1","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"7","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 7]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.15—Proof by induction, contradiction, counterexamples"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}